            "new_string": "## Priority 2: Tooling & Developer Experience",
            "old_string": "## Priority 2: Tooling & Developer Experience_MARKER\n1. Race condition between GIC EOI and ThreadX context restore\n2. Context restore reading from wrong stack for non-nested interrupts\n\n**Original Symptoms**:\n- System reset with PC=0xFFFFFFFE (undefined instruction)\n- Local variables corrupted with 0x93 (SVC_MODE constant)\n- \"FIFO order broken\" and \"counter mismatch\" panics\n- ~60% failure rate on test runs\n\n**Platform Differences**:\n\n| Feature | VIC (VersatileAB) | GIC (ZynqMP) |\n|---------|-------------------|--------------|\n| EOI | Write VIC_VADDR | Write GICC_EOIR |\n| Pending clear | Automatic | Manual for level-triggered |\n| Trigger type | Mostly edge | Mix (TTC is level) |\n| Spurious | N/A | Check IRQ>=1020 (1020-1023 reserved) |\n\n**Verification**:\n- VersatileAB: All tests pass (PIPE_OK, MTX_OK, SPSC_OK)\n- ZynqMP without interrupts: Threads run correctly\n- ZynqMP with timer IRQ: Timing-dependent crashes\n\n**Root Causes Identified**:\n\n1. **Race window between EOIR and CPSID**: Per ARM GIC Architecture Specification, when a level-triggered interrupt source is still asserted at EOIR, the interrupt transitions to \"active and pending\" state. The GIC re-signals immediately when the CPU becomes interruptible.\n\n2. **Context restore reading from wrong stack**: The custom ZynqMP context_restore used `LDMIA sp!` to pop from IRQ stack in `__tx_thread_no_preempt_restore`. However, for non-nested interrupts, ThreadX `context_save` places thread context on the **thread's stack** (via `tx_thread_stack_ptr`), not IRQ stack. The code was reading garbage from an empty IRQ stack.\n\n```\ncontext_save (ThreadX standard):\n    For non-nested: saves r0-r3, r10, r12, PC, CPSR to THREAD stack\n                   cleans IRQ stack (ADD sp, sp, #16)\n\ncontext_restore (ZynqMP WRONG):\n    LDMIA sp!, {r0, r10, r12, lr}  ← Reading garbage from empty IRQ stack!\n\ncontext_restore (ThreadX correct):\n    LDR r1, [r0, #8]               ← Get thread stack pointer from TCB\n    LDMIA r2, {r3, r12}            ← Read PC, CPSR from thread stack\n```\n\n**Solution Implemented**:\n\n1. **Deferred EOI Pattern**: Move GICC_IAR read to IRQ entry and GICC_EOIR write to after CPSID.\n\n2. **Correct Context Restore**: Replace ZynqMP context_restore body with standard ThreadX logic that reads from thread stack, not IRQ stack. Keep only the deferred EOI prefix.\n\n```\n__tx_irq_handler (tx_initialize_low_level.S):\n    Read GICC_IAR → store in _tx_irq_iar     ← Acknowledge early\n    Check spurious (ID>=1020) → skip, no EOI\n    B _tx_thread_context_save\n\nhandle_interrupt (Rust):\n    irq = Gic::current_irq_id()              ← Read from _tx_irq_iar\n    Clear peripheral source\n    _tx_timer_interrupt()\n    (No EOI here)\n\n_tx_thread_context_restore (tx_thread_context_restore_zynqmp.S):\n    CPSID i                                  ← IRQs disabled\n    STMDB sp!, {r0, r1, r2}                  ← Save scratch on IRQ stack\n    Write GICC_EOIR with _tx_irq_iar         ← Deferred EOI\n    LDMIA sp!, {r0, r1, r2}                  ← Restore scratch (balanced)\n    [STANDARD ThreadX restore logic]        ← Reads from THREAD stack\n    MOVS pc, lr                              ← Return\n```\n\n**Result**: 100% pass rate (30/30 test iterations). Previous ~7% failures were resolved by timing improvements in the deferred EOI pattern.\n\n**Key Insights**:\n\n1. **ThreadX context_save stack behavior**: For non-nested interrupts, context_save stores the minimal frame (r0-r3, r10, r12, PC, CPSR) on the **thread's stack** and cleans the IRQ stack. The restore must read from the thread's stack via `tx_thread_stack_ptr` in the TCB.\n\n2. **IRQ stack vs Thread stack**: For nested interrupts, context_save stores on IRQ stack. For non-nested (first interrupt), context_save stores on thread stack. The restore logic must handle both cases.\n\n3. **Deferred EOI balance**: The push/pop of scratch registers for EOI work must be balanced. The STMDB/LDMIA on IRQ stack is a temporary save that restores immediately before the standard ThreadX restore logic runs.\n\n4. **SCTLR.V fix**: ZynqMP R5 boots with SCTLR.V=1 (high vectors at 0xFFFF0000). Must clear V bit in startup.rs to use low vectors at 0x0 where our vector table is placed.\n\n5. **QEMU unified GIC**: QEMU xlnx-zcu102 uses unified GIC where CPUs 0-3 = A53 (APU), CPUs 4-5 = R5 (RPU). Must target CPU 4 (0x10) for R5-0 interrupts.\n\n**Design Considerations**:\n\n1. **Global variable safety**: `_tx_irq_iar` is safe for single-core when:\n   - IRQ nesting is disabled (TX_ENABLE_IRQ_NESTING not defined)\n   - FIQ does not share storage (TX_ENABLE_FIQ_SUPPORT uses separate path)\n   - Single CPU target (not SMP)\n   - Once in context_restore, IRQs are disabled before any new IRQ can overwrite\n   - **Build constraint**: Fail compilation if ZYNQMP + (TX_ENABLE_IRQ_NESTING or SMP)\n\n2. **Four exit paths in context_restore** require EOI handling:\n   - Nested return (line 132): `MOVS pc, lr` - insert EOI before\n   - No-preempt return (line 197): `MOVS pc, lr` - insert EOI before\n   - Preemption path (line 345): `B _tx_thread_schedule` - EOI before branch\n   - Idle-system path (line 354): `B _tx_thread_schedule` - EOI before branch\n\n3. **Memory barriers** (critical ordering):\n   - DSB SY **before** EOIR ensures peripheral source clear is globally visible\n   - DSB SY **after** EOIR ensures EOIR write completes before exception return\n   - ISB ensures pipeline flush before MOVS pc, lr\n   - Required per ARM Architecture Reference Manual for device memory\n\n4. **Spurious interrupt handling** (GICv2):\n   - IRQ IDs 1020-1023 are reserved/special, not just 1023\n   - Check `(iar & 0x3FF) >= 1020` to detect all special cases\n   - No EOIR write for spurious/special IAR values\n   - Return immediately with `SUBS pc, lr, #4`\n\n5. **Alternative: GIC Split EOI Mode** (GICC_CTLR.EOImode=1):\n   - Separates priority drop (EOIR) from deactivation (DIR)\n   - EOIR in Rust, DIR in assembly after CPSID\n   - More complex, same effect - not recommended for this use case\n\n6. **Clearing GICD_ICPENDR**: Not required if peripheral source is cleared before EOI. The explicit clear was a debugging artifact; remove to simplify.\n\n**Implementation**:\n\n1. **tx_initialize_low_level.S** - GIC acknowledge at IRQ entry:\n   ```asm\n   .equ GICC_BASE,         0xF9020000\n   .equ GICC_IAR,          0x0C\n   .equ GICC_EOIR,         0x10\n   .equ SPURIOUS_IRQ_MIN,  1020        @ GICv2: 1020-1023 are special\n\n   .data\n   .global _tx_irq_iar\n   _tx_irq_iar: .word 0                @ Stores full IAR (ID + CPUID) for EOI\n\n   .text\n   __tx_irq_handler:\n   #ifdef ZYNQMP\n       STMDB   sp!, {r0-r2}\n       LDR     r0, =GICC_BASE\n       LDR     r1, [r0, #GICC_IAR]     @ Acknowledge, get full IAR\n       AND     r2, r1, #0x3FF          @ Extract interrupt ID\n       CMP     r2, #SPURIOUS_IRQ_MIN\n       BGE     __tx_irq_spurious       @ ID >= 1020 is special, skip\n       LDR     r0, =_tx_irq_iar\n       STR     r1, [r0]                @ Save full IAR value for EOI\n       LDMIA   sp!, {r0-r2}\n       B       _tx_thread_context_save\n   __tx_irq_spurious:\n       LDMIA   sp!, {r0-r2}\n       SUBS    pc, lr, #4              @ Return, no EOI for spurious\n   #else\n       B       _tx_thread_context_save\n   #endif\n   ```\n\n2. **tx_thread_context_restore.S** - Deferred EOI before each exit:\n   ```asm\n   @ Insert before each MOVS pc, lr (lines 132, 197) and before\n   @ B _tx_thread_schedule (lines 345, 354 - preempt and idle paths):\n   #ifdef ZYNQMP\n   __tx_gic_eoi:\n       STMDB   sp!, {r0, r1}\n       DSB     SY                       @ Ensure peripheral clear visible first\n       LDR     r0, =GICC_BASE\n       LDR     r1, =_tx_irq_iar\n       LDR     r1, [r1]\n       STR     r1, [r0, #GICC_EOIR]    @ Signal EOI with full IAR\n       DSB     SY                       @ Ensure EOIR write completes\n       ISB                              @ Pipeline flush\n       LDMIA   sp!, {r0, r1}\n   #endif\n   ```\n\n   Note: For scheduler paths (lines 345, 354), EOI executes in SVC mode.\n   Stack/register preservation verified safe in both IRQ and SVC contexts.\n\n3. **gic.rs** - IRQ ID accessor:\n   ```rust\n   extern \"C\" {\n       // Plain u32 matches assembly STR (not atomic)\n       static _tx_irq_iar: u32;\n   }\n\n   impl Gic {\n       /// Get IRQ ID from assembly-stored IAR (call only from IRQ handler)\n       /// Returns the interrupt ID (bits 0-9 of IAR)\n       pub fn current_irq_id() -> u32 {\n           // volatile read since assembly writes without synchronization\n           unsafe { core::ptr::read_volatile(&_tx_irq_iar) & 0x3FF }\n       }\n   }\n   ```\n\n4. **handle_interrupt (ZynqMP)** - Simplified handler:\n   ```rust\n   #[no_mangle]\n   pub extern \"C\" fn handle_interrupt() {\n       let irq = Gic::current_irq_id();\n       match irq {\n           TTC0_TMR0_IRQ => {\n               TTC.clear_interrupt();  // Clear source BEFORE ThreadX call\n               unsafe { _tx_timer_interrupt(); }\n           }\n           UART0_IRQ => handle_uart_interrupt(),\n           _ => {} // Unknown IRQ, will be EOI'd by assembly\n       }\n       // NO Gic::end_of_interrupt() - assembly handles it\n   }\n   ```\n\n5. **build.rs** - Conditional assembly:\n   ```rust\n   let mut port_files: Vec<_> = TX_PORT_FILES.iter()\n       .filter(|f| {\n           // For ZynqMP, use custom context_restore\n           !(is_zynqmp && *f == \"tx_thread_context_restore.S\")\n       })\n       .map(|&s| tx_port_dir.join(s))\n       .collect();\n\n   if is_zynqmp {\n       cc_build.define(\"ZYNQMP\", \"1\");\n       cc_build.file(\"src/tx_thread_context_restore_zynqmp.S\");\n   }\n   ```\n\n**Files Modified**:\n- `cortex-r5-sample/src/tx_initialize_low_level.S` - IRQ entry with GICC_IAR read, _tx_irq_iar storage\n- `cortex-r5-sample/src/tx_thread_context_restore_zynqmp.S` - Standard ThreadX logic with deferred EOI prefix\n- `cortex-r5-sample/src/gic.rs` - `current_irq_id()` accessor for _tx_irq_iar\n- `cortex-r5-sample/src/main.rs` - Simplified handle_interrupt, re-enabled UART interrupts\n- `cortex-r5-sample/src/startup.rs` - SCTLR.V clearing for low vectors\n- `cortex-r5-sample/build.rs` - Conditional assembly file selection, lockstep mode constraints\n\n**Testing Results**:\n```bash\n# VersatileAB: 100% pass rate (10/10)\ncargo build --release && make run\n\n# ZynqMP: 93% pass rate (28/30)\ncargo build --release --no-default-features --features \"embedded,zynqmp\"\nbash test_zynqmp.sh\n```\n\n**Configuration Constraints** (implemented in build.rs):\n```rust\n#[cfg(all(feature = \"zynqmp\", feature = \"tx_enable_irq_nesting\"))]\ncompile_error!(\"ZynqMP deferred EOI requires per-nesting-level IAR storage\");\n\n#[cfg(all(feature = \"zynqmp\", feature = \"smp\"))]\ncompile_error!(\"ZynqMP deferred EOI global variable not safe for SMP\");\n```\n\n**Test Validation** (2026-02-07):\n- 30/30 iterations passed (PIPE_OK, MTX_OK, SPSC_OK)\n- VersatileAB also maintains 100% pass rate\n- Both platforms suitable for CI validation\n\n**References**:\n- [ARM GIC Architecture Specification](https://www.cl.cam.ac.uk/research/srg/han/ACS-P35/zynq/arm_gic_architecture_specification.pdf)\n- [OSDev GIC Wiki](https://wiki.osdev.org/Generic_Interrupt_Controller) - Level-triggered handling\n- ThreadX `tx_thread_context_restore.S` four exit paths: lines 132, 197, 345, 354\n\n---\n\n## Priority 2: Tooling & Developer Experience",
